1 SECTION 6. IC 20-33-13.6 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
2 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
3 JULY 1, 2026]:
4 Chapter 13.6. Physical Privacy of Students
5 Sec. 1. (a) As used in this chapter, "multiple occupancy
6 restroom or changing area" means a room or area in a school
7 building that may be used by more than one (1) student at a time
8 and in which students may be in various stages of undress in the
9 presence of other individuals.
10 (b) The term includes a restroom, locker room, changing room,
11 and shower room.
12 (c) The term does not include a family restroom, single
13 occupancy restroom, locker room, changing room, or shower
14 room.
15 Sec. 2. As used in this chapter, "school" means any:
16 (1) school maintained by a school corporation; or
17 (2) charter school;
18 that provides instruction to students in any combination of
19 kindergarten through grade 12.
20 Sec. 3. As used in this chapter, "sleeping quarters" means a
21 room with a bed in which more than one (1) individual is housed
22 overnight.
23 Sec. 4. Each school shall designate each multiple occupancy
24 restroom or changing area as follows:
25 (1) For the exclusive use of the male sex.
26 (2) For the exclusive use of the female sex.
27 Sec. 5. (a) Subject to subsection (b), an individual shall only use
28 a multiple occupancy restroom or changing area that is designated
29 for the sex that is the individual's sex.
30 (b) An individual does not violate subsection (a) if the:
31 (1) multiple occupancy restroom or changing area has been
32 temporarily designated for use by the opposite sex;
33 (2) individual is less than nine (9) years of age and is
34 accompanying their parent or caregiver into a multiple
35 occupancy restroom or changing area; or
36 (3) individual is entering a multiple occupancy restroom or
37 changing area for one (1) or more of the following reasons:
38 (A) For custodial, maintenance, or inspection purposes.
39 (B) To render medical or emergency assistance.
40 (C) To accompany a student needing assistance if the
41 individual assisting the student is the student's parent or
42 caregiver.
SB 182—LS 6808/DI 107

9
1 (D) To provide coaching or athletic training during athletic
2 events, provided the individual providing coaching or
3 training took reasonable steps to ensure no individuals are
4 in a state of undress prior to entering.
5 Sec. 6. During any activity or event authorized by a school in
6 which students share sleeping quarters, a school shall not require
7 a student to share sleeping quarters with a member of the opposite
8 sex, unless the individual of the opposite sex is a member of the
9 student's family.
10 Sec. 7. (a) An individual who encounters an individual violating
11 section 5 of this chapter may bring a civil action against the school
12 corporation or school if the school corporation or school:
13 (1) provided the individual who violated section 5 of this
14 chapter permission to use a multiple occupancy restroom or
15 changing area that is designated for the sex that is not the
16 individual's sex; or
17 (2) failed to take reasonable steps to prohibit the individual
18 who violated section 5 of this chapter from using a multiple
19 occupancy restroom or changing area that is designated for
20 the sex that is not the individual's sex.
21 (b) If a school or school corporation violates section 6 of this
22 chapter, an individual who is directly or indirectly injured as a
23 result of the violation may bring a civil action against the school or
24 school corporation.
25 (c) An action described in this section must be commenced
26 within two (2) years of the violation.
27 Sec. 8. The court may award to an individual who prevails in an
28 action under section 7 of this chapter any of the following:
29 (1) Injunctive relief.
30 (2) Declaratory judgment.
31 (3) Costs and reasonable attorney's fees.
32 Sec. 9. Nothing in this chapter prohibits a school corporation or
33 school from:
34 (1) providing single occupancy sleeping quarters or a single
35 occupancy restroom, locker room, changing room, or shower
36 room; or
37 (2) adopting policies necessary to accommodate individuals
38 protected under the Americans with Disabilities Act (42
39 U.S.C. 12101 et seq.) and any amendments and regulations
40 related to the Act.
41 Sec. 10. The provisions of this chapter are severable as provided
42 in IC 1-1-1-8(b).
SB 182—LS 6808/DI 107

